   Technol; Univ Hong Kong; Univ Macau; Shenzhen Acad Robot},
Abstract = {This paper proposes a novel method for anthropomorphic dual-arm robots
   to plan bimanual transport tasks, considering the feature of human-like
   structure and utilizing synergies to reduce the dimension of the system.
   Unlike conventional methods in which the trajectory of the transported
   object is explicitly prescribed in the operational space, the proposed
   method plans the motion upon intrinsic variables from both arms and
   produce the trajectory in an indirect way. Thus, the proposed method is
   a model-based ``joint space{''} method and exploits the coordination of
   the arms in the motion planning procedure. The motion planning is
   divided into translation planning and orientation stabilization. Only
   the final positions of the wrist centers need to be specified for
   translation planning; the object's orientation will adapt following the
   translation. Simulation is conducted to verify the feasibility of the
   proposed method. Comparison with the conventional method is performed to
   demonstrate the features of the proposed method.},
