Pages = {4100-4107},
Month = {OCT},
Abstract = {A key problem in robotics is enabling an autonomous agent to perform
   human-like arm movements in close proximity to another human. However,
   modeling the human decision and control process of the movement during
   dyadic interaction presents a challenge. Although, most prior approaches
   rely on multicomponent robot motion planning architectures, we use data
   of two humans performing interfering arm reaching movements to extract
   and transfer interaction behavior control skill to a robotic agent. A
   recurrent neural network-based framework is constructed to learn a
   policy that computes control signals for a robot end effector in order
   to replace one human. The learned policy is benchmarked against unseen
   interaction data and a state-of-the-art learning from demonstration
   framework in simulated scenarios. We compare several architectures and
   investigate a new activation function of three stacked tanh(). The
   results show that the proposed framework successfully learns a policy to
   imitate human movement behavior control during dyadic interaction. The
   policy is transferred to a real robot and its feasibility for
   close-proximity human-robot interaction is shown.},
